choices.text:
the mandatory hijab everyone (that’s women only because men are not mandated to cover their heads) must wear. It is very uncomfortable, thank God I do not hair, otherwise I definitely would have plucked it all out in frustration. Nobody expects to have our parents and the government dictate us how to look, dress and behave. For instance there is no law to prevent men from wearing miniskirts or make up but I’m forced to abide by the Islamic dress code. That’s why I can’t understand why I was told not to bother exercising at the training hall to avoid suspicion of studying capoeira, the self-defense martial art I have been studying for over a year in Ottawa. To be honest I was very upset at first because I thought it was very unfair and going to the training hall is very important to my well-being. Luckily for me most of my friends who started the same year as me (I’m in my third year) wear a hijab and still go to classes…So sometimes I use the cover of their hijab and of course their supporting behavior to avoid suspicion and go to class, but in my case I achieved this covert oppression itself is an honor and deserves a two-minute applause.

My second biggest issue, which probably makes beginning capoeira practitioners the most nervous is the absence of randomly appointed guards around the training hall (like they have at mosques, churches and different public locations in Iran).
